  "text": "The MMAS has provided the ®rst incidence rates for ED (Table 1) . Incidence rates, which comprise new cases of a condition, or a transition from a nondiseased to a diseased state, obviously require prospective data for their calculation. Prior to the MMAS, the only published estimate of the incidence of ED was from a convenience sample of 3250 men aged 26 ± 83 y visiting a preventive medicine clinic in Texas between 1987 and 1991. [CITATION_1] Johannes et al 9 has recently reported age-category speci®c incidence rates for ED and shows how they differ by sociodemographic status (education, income) and also health status.",
